<Link id="l00008" /><CodeLine lineNumber="8"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00009" /><CodeLine lineNumber="9"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Target-independent, SSA-based data flow graph for register data flow (RDF)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00010" /><CodeLine lineNumber="10"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// for a non-SSA program representation (e.g. post-RA machine code).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="11"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="12"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="13"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#42;&#42;&#42; Introduction</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="14"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="15"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The RDF graph is a collection of nodes, each of which denotes some element</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="16"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// of the program. There are two main types of such elements: code and refe-</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00017" /><CodeLine lineNumber="17"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// rences. Conceptually, &quot;code&quot; is something that represents the structure</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00018" /><CodeLine lineNumber="18"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// of the program, e.g. basic block or a statement, while &quot;reference&quot; is an</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00019" /><CodeLine lineNumber="19"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// instance of accessing a register, e.g. a definition or a use. Nodes are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00020" /><CodeLine lineNumber="20"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// connected with each other based on the structure of the program (such as</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00021" /><CodeLine lineNumber="21"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// blocks, instructions, etc.), and based on the data flow (e.g. reaching</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00022" /><CodeLine lineNumber="22"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// definitions, reached uses, etc.). The single-reaching-definition principle</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00023" /><CodeLine lineNumber="23"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// of SSA is generally observed, although, due to the non-SSA representation</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00024" /><CodeLine lineNumber="24"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// of the program, there are some differences between the graph and a &quot;pure&quot;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00025" /><CodeLine lineNumber="25"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// SSA representation.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="26"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#42;&#42;&#42; Implementation remarks</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Since the graph can contain a large number of nodes, memory consumption</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// was one of the major design considerations. As a result, there is a single</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// base class NodeBase which defines all members used by all possible derived</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// classes. The members are arranged in a union, and a derived class cannot</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// add any data members of its own. Each derived class only defines the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// functional interface, i.e. member functions. NodeBase must be a POD,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// which implies that all of its members must also be PODs.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Since nodes need to be connected with other nodes, pointers have been</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// replaced with 32-bit identifiers: each node has an id of type NodeId.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// There are mapping functions in the graph that translate between actual</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// memory addresses and the corresponding identifiers.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// A node id of 0 is equivalent to nullptr.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#42;&#42;&#42; Structure of the graph</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// A code node is always a collection of other nodes. For example, a code</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// node corresponding to a basic block will contain code nodes corresponding</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// to instructions. In turn, a code node corresponding to an instruction will</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="49"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// contain a list of reference nodes that correspond to the definitions and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// uses of registers in that instruction. The members are arranged into a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// circular list, which is yet another consequence of the effort to save</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00052" /><CodeLine lineNumber="52"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// memory: for each member node it should be possible to obtain its owner,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00053" /><CodeLine lineNumber="53"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// and it should be possible to access all other members. There are other</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ways to accomplish that, but the circular list seemed the most natural.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// +- CodeNode -+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// |            | &lt;---------------------------------------------------+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// +-+--------+-+                                                     |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   |FirstM  |LastM                                                  |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00060" /><CodeLine lineNumber="60"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   |        +-------------------------------------+                 |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00061" /><CodeLine lineNumber="61"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   |                                              |                 |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="62"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   V                                              V                 |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="63"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  +----------+ Next +----------+ Next       Next +----------+ Next  |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |          |-----&gt;|          |-----&gt; ... -----&gt;|          |-----&gt;-+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  +- Member -+      +- Member -+                 +- Member -+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="66"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00067" /><CodeLine lineNumber="67"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The order of members is such that related reference nodes (see below)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="68"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// should be contiguous on the member list.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00069" /><CodeLine lineNumber="69"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00070" /><CodeLine lineNumber="70"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// A reference node is a node that encapsulates an access to a register,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00071" /><CodeLine lineNumber="71"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// in other words, data flowing into or out of a register. There are two</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00072" /><CodeLine lineNumber="72"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// major kinds of reference nodes: defs and uses. A def node will contain</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00073" /><CodeLine lineNumber="73"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the id of the first reached use, and the id of the first reached def.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00074" /><CodeLine lineNumber="74"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Each def and use will contain the id of the reaching def, and also the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00075" /><CodeLine lineNumber="75"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// id of the next reached def (for def nodes) or use (for use nodes).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00076" /><CodeLine lineNumber="76"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The &quot;next node sharing the same reaching def&quot; is denoted as &quot;sibling&quot;.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00077" /><CodeLine lineNumber="77"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// In summary:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00078" /><CodeLine lineNumber="78"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Def node contains: reaching def, sibling, first reached def, and first</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00079" /><CodeLine lineNumber="79"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// reached use.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00080" /><CodeLine lineNumber="80"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Use node contains: reaching def and sibling.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00081" /><CodeLine lineNumber="81"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00082" /><CodeLine lineNumber="82"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// +-- DefNode --+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00083" /><CodeLine lineNumber="83"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// | R2 = ...    | &lt;---+--------------------+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00084" /><CodeLine lineNumber="84"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ++---------+--+     |                    |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00085" /><CodeLine lineNumber="85"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |Reached  |Reached |                    |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00086" /><CodeLine lineNumber="86"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |Def      |Use     |                    |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00087" /><CodeLine lineNumber="87"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |         |        |Reaching            |Reaching</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00088" /><CodeLine lineNumber="88"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |         V        |Def                 |Def</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00089" /><CodeLine lineNumber="89"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |      +-- UseNode --+ Sib  +-- UseNode --+ Sib       Sib</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00090" /><CodeLine lineNumber="90"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |      | ... = R2    |-----&gt;| ... = R2    |----&gt; ... ----&gt; 0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00091" /><CodeLine lineNumber="91"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |      +-------------+      +-------------+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00092" /><CodeLine lineNumber="92"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  V</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00093" /><CodeLine lineNumber="93"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// +-- DefNode --+ Sib</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00094" /><CodeLine lineNumber="94"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// | R2 = ...    |----&gt; ...</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00095" /><CodeLine lineNumber="95"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ++---------+--+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00096" /><CodeLine lineNumber="96"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |         |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00097" /><CodeLine lineNumber="97"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  |         |</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00098" /><CodeLine lineNumber="98"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ...       ...</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00099" /><CodeLine lineNumber="99"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00100" /><CodeLine lineNumber="100"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// To get a full picture, the circular lists connecting blocks within a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00101" /><CodeLine lineNumber="101"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// function, instructions within a block, etc. should be superimposed with</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00102" /><CodeLine lineNumber="102"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the def-def, def-use links shown above.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00103" /><CodeLine lineNumber="103"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// To illustrate this, consider a small example in a pseudo-assembly:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00104" /><CodeLine lineNumber="104"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// foo:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00105" /><CodeLine lineNumber="105"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   add r2, r0, r1   ; r2 = r0+r1</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00106" /><CodeLine lineNumber="106"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   addi r0, r2, 1   ; r0 = r2+1</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00107" /><CodeLine lineNumber="107"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   ret r0           ; return value in r0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00108" /><CodeLine lineNumber="108"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00109" /><CodeLine lineNumber="109"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The graph (in a format used by the debugging functions) would look like:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00110" /><CodeLine lineNumber="110"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00111" /><CodeLine lineNumber="111"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   DFG dump:&#91;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00112" /><CodeLine lineNumber="112"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   f1: Function foo</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00113" /><CodeLine lineNumber="113"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   b2: === %bb.0 === preds(0), succs(0):</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00114" /><CodeLine lineNumber="114"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   p3: phi &#91;d4&lt;r0&gt;(,d12,u9):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00115" /><CodeLine lineNumber="115"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   p5: phi &#91;d6&lt;r1&gt;(,,u10):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00116" /><CodeLine lineNumber="116"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   s7: add &#91;d8&lt;r2&gt;(,,u13):, u9&lt;r0&gt;(d4):, u10&lt;r1&gt;(d6):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00117" /><CodeLine lineNumber="117"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   s11: addi &#91;d12&lt;r0&gt;(d4,,u15):, u13&lt;r2&gt;(d8):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00118" /><CodeLine lineNumber="118"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   s14: ret &#91;u15&lt;r0&gt;(d12):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00119" /><CodeLine lineNumber="119"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   &#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00120" /><CodeLine lineNumber="120"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00121" /><CodeLine lineNumber="121"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The f1, b2, p3, etc. are node ids. The letter is prepended to indicate the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00122" /><CodeLine lineNumber="122"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// kind of the node (i.e. f - function, b - basic block, p - phi, s - state-</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00123" /><CodeLine lineNumber="123"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ment, d - def, u - use).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00124" /><CodeLine lineNumber="124"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The format of a def node is:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00125" /><CodeLine lineNumber="125"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   dN&lt;R&gt;(rd,d,u):sib,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00126" /><CodeLine lineNumber="126"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// where</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00127" /><CodeLine lineNumber="127"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   N   - numeric node id,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00128" /><CodeLine lineNumber="128"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   R   - register being defined</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00129" /><CodeLine lineNumber="129"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   rd  - reaching def,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00130" /><CodeLine lineNumber="130"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   d   - reached def,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00131" /><CodeLine lineNumber="131"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   u   - reached use,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00132" /><CodeLine lineNumber="132"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   sib - sibling.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00133" /><CodeLine lineNumber="133"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The format of a use node is:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00134" /><CodeLine lineNumber="134"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   uN&lt;R&gt;&#91;!&#93;(rd):sib,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00135" /><CodeLine lineNumber="135"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// where</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00136" /><CodeLine lineNumber="136"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   N   - numeric node id,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00137" /><CodeLine lineNumber="137"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   R   - register being used,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00138" /><CodeLine lineNumber="138"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   rd  - reaching def,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00139" /><CodeLine lineNumber="139"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   sib - sibling.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00140" /><CodeLine lineNumber="140"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Possible annotations (usually preceding the node id):</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00141" /><CodeLine lineNumber="141"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   +   - preserving def,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00142" /><CodeLine lineNumber="142"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   ~   - clobbering def,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00143" /><CodeLine lineNumber="143"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   &quot;   - shadow ref (follows the node id),</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00144" /><CodeLine lineNumber="144"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   !   - fixed register (appears after register name).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00145" /><CodeLine lineNumber="145"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00146" /><CodeLine lineNumber="146"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The circular lists are not explicit in the dump.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00147" /><CodeLine lineNumber="147"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00148" /><CodeLine lineNumber="148"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00149" /><CodeLine lineNumber="149"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#42;&#42;&#42; Node attributes</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00150" /><CodeLine lineNumber="150"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00151" /><CodeLine lineNumber="151"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// NodeBase has a member &quot;Attrs&quot;, which is the primary way of determining</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00152" /><CodeLine lineNumber="152"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the node&#39;s characteristics. The fields in this member decide whether</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00153" /><CodeLine lineNumber="153"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the node is a code node or a reference node (i.e. node&#39;s &quot;type&quot;), then</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00154" /><CodeLine lineNumber="154"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// within each type, the &quot;kind&quot; determines what specifically this node</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00155" /><CodeLine lineNumber="155"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// represents. The remaining bits, &quot;flags&quot;, contain additional information</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00156" /><CodeLine lineNumber="156"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// that is even more detailed than the &quot;kind&quot;.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00157" /><CodeLine lineNumber="157"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// CodeNode&#39;s kinds are:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00158" /><CodeLine lineNumber="158"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Phi:   Phi node, members are reference nodes.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00159" /><CodeLine lineNumber="159"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Stmt:  Statement, members are reference nodes.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00160" /><CodeLine lineNumber="160"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Block: Basic block, members are instruction nodes (i.e. Phi or Stmt).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00161" /><CodeLine lineNumber="161"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Func:  The whole function. The members are basic block nodes.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00162" /><CodeLine lineNumber="162"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// RefNode&#39;s kinds are:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00163" /><CodeLine lineNumber="163"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Use.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00164" /><CodeLine lineNumber="164"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Def.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00165" /><CodeLine lineNumber="165"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00166" /><CodeLine lineNumber="166"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Meaning of flags:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00167" /><CodeLine lineNumber="167"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Preserving: applies only to defs. A preserving def is one that can</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00168" /><CodeLine lineNumber="168"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   preserve some of the original bits among those that are included in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00169" /><CodeLine lineNumber="169"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   the register associated with that def. For example, if R0 is a 32-bit</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00170" /><CodeLine lineNumber="170"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   register, but a def can only change the lower 16 bits, then it will</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00171" /><CodeLine lineNumber="171"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   be marked as preserving.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00172" /><CodeLine lineNumber="172"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Shadow: a reference that has duplicates holding additional reaching</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00173" /><CodeLine lineNumber="173"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   defs (see more below).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00174" /><CodeLine lineNumber="174"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Clobbering: applied only to defs, indicates that the value generated</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00175" /><CodeLine lineNumber="175"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   by this def is unspecified. A typical example would be volatile registers</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00176" /><CodeLine lineNumber="176"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   after function calls.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00177" /><CodeLine lineNumber="177"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Fixed: the register in this def/use cannot be replaced with any other</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00178" /><CodeLine lineNumber="178"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   register. A typical case would be a parameter register to a call, or</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00179" /><CodeLine lineNumber="179"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   the register with the return value from a function.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00180" /><CodeLine lineNumber="180"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Undef: the register in this reference the register is assumed to have</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00181" /><CodeLine lineNumber="181"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   no pre-existing value, even if it appears to be reached by some def.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00182" /><CodeLine lineNumber="182"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   This is typically used to prevent keeping registers artificially live</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00183" /><CodeLine lineNumber="183"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   in cases when they are defined via predicated instructions. For example:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00184" /><CodeLine lineNumber="184"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//     r0 = add-if-true cond, r10, r11                (1)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00185" /><CodeLine lineNumber="185"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//     r0 = add-if-false cond, r12, r13, implicit r0  (2)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00186" /><CodeLine lineNumber="186"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//     ... = r0                                       (3)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00187" /><CodeLine lineNumber="187"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   Before (1), r0 is not intended to be live, and the use of r0 in (3) is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00188" /><CodeLine lineNumber="188"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   not meant to be reached by any def preceding (1). However, since the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00189" /><CodeLine lineNumber="189"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   defs in (1) and (2) are both preserving, these properties alone would</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00190" /><CodeLine lineNumber="190"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   imply that the use in (3) may indeed be reached by some prior def.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00191" /><CodeLine lineNumber="191"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   Adding Undef flag to the def in (1) prevents that. The Undef flag</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00192" /><CodeLine lineNumber="192"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   may be applied to both defs and uses.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00193" /><CodeLine lineNumber="193"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Dead: applies only to defs. The value coming out of a &quot;dead&quot; def is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00194" /><CodeLine lineNumber="194"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   assumed to be unused, even if the def appears to be reaching other defs</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00195" /><CodeLine lineNumber="195"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   or uses. The motivation for this flag comes from dead defs on function</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00196" /><CodeLine lineNumber="196"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   calls: there is no way to determine if such a def is dead without</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00197" /><CodeLine lineNumber="197"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   analyzing the target&#39;s ABI. Hence the graph should contain this info,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00198" /><CodeLine lineNumber="198"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   as it is unavailable otherwise. On the other hand, a def without any</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00199" /><CodeLine lineNumber="199"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   uses on a typical instruction is not the intended target for this flag.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00200" /><CodeLine lineNumber="200"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00201" /><CodeLine lineNumber="201"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#42;&#42;&#42; Shadow references</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00202" /><CodeLine lineNumber="202"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00203" /><CodeLine lineNumber="203"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// It may happen that a super-register can have two (or more) non-overlapping</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00204" /><CodeLine lineNumber="204"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// sub-registers. When both of these sub-registers are defined and followed</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00205" /><CodeLine lineNumber="205"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// by a use of the super-register, the use of the super-register will not</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00206" /><CodeLine lineNumber="206"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// have a unique reaching def: both defs of the sub-registers need to be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00207" /><CodeLine lineNumber="207"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// accounted for. In such cases, a duplicate use of the super-register is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00208" /><CodeLine lineNumber="208"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// added and it points to the extra reaching def. Both uses are marked with</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00209" /><CodeLine lineNumber="209"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// a flag &quot;shadow&quot;. Example:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00210" /><CodeLine lineNumber="210"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Assume t0 is a super-register of r0 and r1, r0 and r1 do not overlap:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00211" /><CodeLine lineNumber="211"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   set r0, 1        ; r0 = 1</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00212" /><CodeLine lineNumber="212"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   set r1, 1        ; r1 = 1</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00213" /><CodeLine lineNumber="213"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   addi t1, t0, 1   ; t1 = t0+1</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00214" /><CodeLine lineNumber="214"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00215" /><CodeLine lineNumber="215"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The DFG:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00216" /><CodeLine lineNumber="216"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   s1: set &#91;d2&lt;r0&gt;(,,u9):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00217" /><CodeLine lineNumber="217"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   s3: set &#91;d4&lt;r1&gt;(,,u10):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00218" /><CodeLine lineNumber="218"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   s5: addi &#91;d6&lt;t1&gt;(,,):, u7&quot;&lt;t0&gt;(d2):, u8&quot;&lt;t0&gt;(d4):&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00219" /><CodeLine lineNumber="219"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00220" /><CodeLine lineNumber="220"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The statement s5 has two use nodes for t0: u7&quot; and u9&quot;. The quotation</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00221" /><CodeLine lineNumber="221"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// mark &quot; indicates that the node is a shadow.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00222" /><CodeLine lineNumber="222"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00223" /><CodeLine lineNumber="223"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00224" /><CodeLine lineNumber="224"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#ifndef LLVM&#95;CODEGEN&#95;RDFGRAPH&#95;H</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00225" /><CodeLine lineNumber="225"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;CODEGEN&#95;RDFGRAPH&#95;H</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00226" /><CodeLine lineNumber="226"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00227" /><CodeLine lineNumber="227"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &quot;<a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/codegen/rdfregisters-h">RDFRegisters.h</a>&quot;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00228" /><CodeLine lineNumber="228"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &quot;<a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/arrayref-h">llvm/ADT/ArrayRef.h</a>&quot;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00229" /><CodeLine lineNumber="229"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &quot;<a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/smallvector-h">llvm/ADT/SmallVector.h</a>&quot;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00230" /><CodeLine lineNumber="230"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &quot;<a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/mc/lanebitmask-h">llvm/MC/LaneBitmask.h</a>&quot;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00231" /><CodeLine lineNumber="231"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &quot;<a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/allocator-h">llvm/Support/Allocator.h</a>&quot;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00232" /><CodeLine lineNumber="232"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &quot;<a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/mathextras-h">llvm/Support/MathExtras.h</a>&quot;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00233" /><CodeLine lineNumber="233"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;cassert&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00234" /><CodeLine lineNumber="234"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;cstdint&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00235" /><CodeLine lineNumber="235"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;cstring&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00236" /><CodeLine lineNumber="236"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;map&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00237" /><CodeLine lineNumber="237"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;memory&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00238" /><CodeLine lineNumber="238"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;set&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00239" /><CodeLine lineNumber="239"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;unordered&#95;map&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00240" /><CodeLine lineNumber="240"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;utility&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00241" /><CodeLine lineNumber="241"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#include &lt;vector&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00242" /><CodeLine lineNumber="242"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00243" /><CodeLine lineNumber="243"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// RDF uses uint32&#95;t to refer to registers. This is to ensure that the type</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00244" /><CodeLine lineNumber="244"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// size remains specific. In other places, registers are often stored using</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00245" /><CodeLine lineNumber="245"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// unsigned.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00246" /><CodeLine lineNumber="246"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">static&#95;assert</span><span class="doxyHighlight">(</span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">sizeof</span><span class="doxyHighlight">(uint32&#95;t) == </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">sizeof</span><span class="doxyHighlight">(unsigned), </span><span class="doxyHighlightStringLiteral">&quot;Those should be equal&quot;</span><span class="doxyHighlight">);</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00247" /><CodeLine lineNumber="247"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00248" /><CodeLine lineNumber="248"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">namespace </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm">llvm</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00257" /><CodeLine lineNumber="257"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targetinstrinfo">TargetInstrInfo</a>;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00259" /><CodeLine lineNumber="259"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00260" /><CodeLine lineNumber="260" lineLink="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/rdf"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">namespace </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/rdf">rdf</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00261" /><CodeLine lineNumber="261"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00262" /><CodeLine lineNumber="262" lineLink="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/rdf/#a9c5c1abf54c7f5aaf8add770214aba5d"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">using </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/rdf/#a9c5c1abf54c7f5aaf8add770214aba5d">NodeId</a> = uint32&#95;t;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00263" /><CodeLine lineNumber="263"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00264" /><CodeLine lineNumber="264"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">struct </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/dataflowgraph">DataFlowGraph</a>;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00265" /><CodeLine lineNumber="265"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00266" /><CodeLine lineNumber="266" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">struct </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs">NodeAttrs</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00267" /><CodeLine lineNumber="267"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// clang-format off</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00268" /><CodeLine lineNumber="268"><span class="doxyHighlight">  enum : uint16&#95;t &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00269" /><CodeLine lineNumber="269" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121dafbb338819a49cc97e98aaba2a6cd258b"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121dafbb338819a49cc97e98aaba2a6cd258b">None</a>          = 0x0000,   </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Nothing</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Types: 2 bits</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="272" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121da778034fbdbc630510fb9082f31a985cf"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121da778034fbdbc630510fb9082f31a985cf">TypeMask</a>      = 0x0003,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="273" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121da3897c75682d603726fd11a4ce74fbfdf"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121da3897c75682d603726fd11a4ce74fbfdf">Code</a>          = 0x0001,   </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// 01, Container</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121da1f251b754ed5bef25dc1f69e6bd845ea"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeattrs/#a96730c2fe7aaa0b753e7483d1e6a121da1f251b754ed5bef25dc1f69e6bd845ea">Ref</a>           = 0x0002,   </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// 10, Reference</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00394" /><CodeLine lineNumber="394"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00395" /><CodeLine lineNumber="395"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Fast memory allocation and translation between node id and node address.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00396" /><CodeLine lineNumber="396"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This is really the same idea as the one underlying the &quot;bump pointer</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00397" /><CodeLine lineNumber="397"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// allocator&quot;, the difference being in the translation. A node id is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00398" /><CodeLine lineNumber="398"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// composed of two components: the index of the block in which it was</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00399" /><CodeLine lineNumber="399"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// allocated, and the index within the block. With the default settings,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00400" /><CodeLine lineNumber="400"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// where the number of nodes per block is 4096, the node id (minus 1) is:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00401" /><CodeLine lineNumber="401"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00402" /><CodeLine lineNumber="402"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// bit position:                11             0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00403" /><CodeLine lineNumber="403"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// +----------------------------+--------------+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00404" /><CodeLine lineNumber="404"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// | Index of the block         |Index in block|</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00405" /><CodeLine lineNumber="405"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// +----------------------------+--------------+</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00406" /><CodeLine lineNumber="406"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00407" /><CodeLine lineNumber="407"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The actual node id is the above plus 1, to avoid creating a node id of 0</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00408" /><CodeLine lineNumber="408"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00409" /><CodeLine lineNumber="409"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This method significantly improved the build time, compared to using maps</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00410" /><CodeLine lineNumber="410"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// (std::unordered&#95;map or DenseMap) to translate between pointers and ids.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00411" /><CodeLine lineNumber="411" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeallocator"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">struct </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeallocator/#aefe039eea038ca29eaed3f43b7eea8ee">NodeAllocator</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00412" /><CodeLine lineNumber="412"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Amount of storage for a single node.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00413" /><CodeLine lineNumber="413" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeallocator/#abf0240b783f3a317d9f88149d48d59f7a3c40461446c69ef8ed66219b79503c6b"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">enum</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> &#123; <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeallocator/#abf0240b783f3a317d9f88149d48d59f7a3c40461446c69ef8ed66219b79503c6b">NodeMemSize</a> = 32 &#125;;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00414" /><CodeLine lineNumber="414"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00415" /><CodeLine lineNumber="415" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeallocator/#aefe039eea038ca29eaed3f43b7eea8ee"><span class="doxyHighlight">  <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/rdf/nodeallocator/#aefe039eea038ca29eaed3f43b7eea8ee">NodeAllocator</a>(uint32&#95;t NPB = 4096)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00416" /><CodeLine lineNumber="416"><span class="doxyHighlight">      : NodesPerBlock(NPB), BitsPerIndex(<a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#a646986783f35e0fef8988f0f28d2589f">Log2&#95;32</a>(NPB)),</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00417" /><CodeLine lineNumber="417"><span class="doxyHighlight">        IndexMask((1 &lt;&lt; BitsPerIndex) - 1) &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00418" /><CodeLine lineNumber="418"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/amdgpu/silowercontrolflow-cpp/#a4868c5d81c5ccc98c47aeab6244346a0">assert</a>(<a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#a6dec2b5d3e04b47adf4d918d678e81c9">isPowerOf2&#95;32</a>(NPB));</span></CodeLine>
